{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{notability|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox company | name = Creative Assembly Sofia | logo = Creative Assembly Sofia.png | former_name = {{Unbulleted list|Black Sea Studios Ltd.{{efn|name="BSS-BG"|{{lang-bg|Блек Сий Студиос ЕООД|translit=Blek Siĭ Studios EOOD}}}} {{small|(2001–2008)}}|Crytek Black Sea Ltd.{{efn|name="CBS-BG"|{{lang-bg|Крайтек Блек Сий ЕООД|translit=Kraĭtek Blek Siĭ EOOD}}}} {{small|(2008–2017)}}}} | native_name = Криейтив Асембли София | native_name_lang = bg | romanized_name = Krieĭtiv Asembli Sofiya | type = [[Subsidiary]] | industry = [[Video game industry]] | founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2001|05|07}} | founder = Vesselin Handjiev | hq_location_city = [[Sofia]] | hq_location_country = [[Bulgaria]] | key_people = | products = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Knights of Honor (video game)|Knights of Honor]]''|''[[WorldShift]]''}} | num_employees = 60 | num_employees_year = 2017 | parent = {{Unbulleted list|[[Crytek]] {{small|(2008–2017)}}|[[Creative Assembly]] {{small|(2017–present)}}}} | website = }} [[File:Black Sea Studios.jpeg|thumb|right|Former Black Sea Studios logo]] [[File:Crytek Black Sea.png|thumb|right|Former Crytek Black Sea logo]] '''Creative Assembly Sofia'''{{efn|name="CAS-BG"|{{lang-bg|Криейтив Асембли София|Krieĭtiv Asembli Sofiya}}}} (formerly '''Black Sea Studios Ltd.'''{{efn|name="BSS-BG"}} and later '''Crytek Black Sea Ltd.'''{{efn|name="CBS-BG"}}) is a [[Bulgaria]]n [[video game developer]] based in [[Sofia]]. The company was established by Vesselin Handjiev as Black Sea Studios in 2001.<ref>https://www.gamespot.com/articles/black-sea-studios-founded/1100-2716273/</ref> The company is best known for its 2004 title ''[[Knights of Honor (video game)|Knights of Honor]]'', a historical [[real-time strategy]] game released for [[Microsoft Windows]], and for the 2008 science fiction real-time strategy title ''[[WorldShift]]''.
In July 2008, German developer and publisher [[Crytek]] announced their acquisition of the studio, and renamed it Crytek Black Sea.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/crytek-acquires-black-sea-studios |title=Crytek acquires Black Sea Studios |last=Lee |first=James |date=22 July 2008 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |publisher=[[Gamer Network]] |accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref> In May 2014, Crytek announced the development of their own [[multiplayer online battle arena]] game using the [[CryEngine]], titled ''[[Arena of Fate]]'' and under development at the Sofia studio. The game was shown at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2014|E3 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/22/crytek-announces-arena-of-fate-for-pc-and-consoles |title=Crytek Announces Arena of Fate For PC and Consoles |last=Karmali |first=Luke |date=22 May 2014 |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[IGN Entertainment]] |accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>
In November 2016, the founder and Director of the studio Vesselin Handjiev left and a month later announced the formation of a new game company, Black Sea Games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2016-12-24-crytek-sofia-developers-re-form-black-sea-games |title=Crytek Sofia developers re-form Black Sea Games |last=Dring |first=Christopher |date=24 December 2016 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |publisher=[[Gamer Network]] |accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref>
In December 2016, Crytek announced that it would shut down five of its international studios, due to financial troubles, of which Crytek Black Sea was put up for sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/crytek-shuts-down-five-studios-amid-financial-diff/1100-6446417/ |title=Crytek Shuts Down Five Studios Amid Financial Difficulties |last=Dayus |first=Oscar |date=20 December 2016 |website=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/12/20/crytek-closes-five-studios-after-failing-to-pay-workers/ |title=Crytek closes five studios after reportedly failing to pay workers |last=Caldwell |first=Brendan |date=20 December 2016 |website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, it was announced that the studio was acquired by British developer [[Creative Assembly]] (itself owned by [[Sega]]), and was renamed Creative Assembly Sofia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/creative-assembly-acquires-arena-of-fate-developer-crytek-black-sea/ |title=Creative Assembly acquires Arena of Fate developer Crytek Black Sea |last=Donnelly |first=Joe |date=7 March 2017 |website=[[PC Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future US]] |accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>
