{{Infobox European Parliament constituency |title = Essex South |map = Image:Europarl logo.svg |mapcaption = [[European Parliament]] logo |created = 1994 |dissolved = 1999 |meps = 1 |memberstate = United Kingdom |sources = [http://www.election.demon.co.uk/] }} '''Essex South''' was a [[European Parliament constituency|constituency]] of the [[European Parliament]] located in the [[United Kingdom]], electing one [[member of the European Parliament]] by the [[first-past-the-post]] electoral system. Created in [[European Parliament election, 1994 (United Kingdom)|1994]] from parts of [[Essex South West (European Parliament constituency)|Essex South West]] and [[Essex North East (European Parliament constituency)|Essex North East]], it was abolished in [[European Parliament election, 1994 (United Kingdom)|1999]] on the adoption of [[proportional representation]] for [[Elections in the European Union|European elections]] in the United Kingdom. It was succeeded by the [[East of England (European Parliament constituency)|East of England region]].
==Boundaries==
It consisted of the [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|parliamentary constituencies]] of [[Basildon (UK Parliament constituency)|Basildon]], [[Billericay (UK Parliament constituency)|Billericay]], [[Castle Point (UK Parliament constituency)|Castle Point]], [[Rochford (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochford]], [[Southend East (UK Parliament constituency)|Southend East]], [[Southend West (UK Parliament constituency)|Southend West]] and [[Thurrock (UK Parliament constituency)|Thurrock]].<ref>''The European Parliament 1994-1999 : MEPs and European constituencies in the United Kingdom'', London : UK Office of the European Parliament, November 1994.</ref> Basildon, Billericay and Thurrock had previously been part of Essex South West while Castle Point, Southend East, Southend West and much of Rochford had been part of Essex North East.
The entire area became part of the East of England constituency in 1999.
