{{Expand French|Garde champêtre en France|date=October 2013}}
{{Refimprove|date=March 2016}}
[[File:Ecusson des GCT.jpg|thumb|Garde champêtre patch]]
[[File:ZOE Police Rurale.jpg|thumb|Renault électrique "Zoé" of the police rurale]]

A '''''garde champêtre''''' ({{lang-fr|lit. rural guard}}) is the combination of a [[forest ranger]], [[game warden]] and [[police officer]] in certain rural communes in [[France]]. 
==Organization==
Their job is to report to the local [[mayor]]. Many of these officers carry firearms (they commonly face poachers, many of whom are themselves armed) and other weapons. Mayors decide which weapons to provide them with, but ''gardes champêtres'' can purchase, retain and carry a much wider range of weapons than the urban police [[Municipal Police (France)|(''police municipale)'']] are allowed. They are not under the supervision of the [[French Gendarmerie|Gendarmerie]] but under the mayor's, their employer.

==History and future development==
From 1791 to 1958 it was compulsory for each rural commune to employ a ''garde champêtre''. Since then many formerly rural communes are heavily or totally urbanised and the number in post has been shrinking every year. A draft law in 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichLoiPreparation.do;jsessionid=727BB060B2116F04650F4E7247A65511.tpdjo09v_2?idDocument=JORFDOLE000029098353&type=general&typeLoi=prop&legislature=14 |title=Dossiers législatifs - Proposition de loi visant à créer des polices territoriales et portant dispositions diverses relatives à leur organisation et leur fonctionnement |language=fr |website=Legifrance |date= |accessdate=2016-03-15}}</ref> provided for the integration of the remaining ''gardes champêtres'' with the ''police municipale'' and the highway control officers (''agents de surveillance de la voie publique'') into a new ''police territoriale''.
==Uniforms and rank insignia==
[[File:Pucelle métallique.png|thumb|Metal badge]][[File:Ecusson garde champetre territorial.jpg|thumb|200px|Cloth patch]]
Their uniforms are not regulated and are at the mayor's discretion; they are traditionally green. The only compulsory element of their dress is a metal badge or cloth patch bearing the words: "LA LOI" (the law), the name of the commune and that of the ''garde champêtre''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCodeArticle.do;jsessionid=2AF5BC1E2DD5600D61335543BB150989.tpdjo07v_2?cidTexte=LEGITEXT000025503132&idArticle=LEGIARTI000028286220&dateTexte=20140223&categorieLien=cid#LEGIARTI000028286220 |title=Code de la sécurité intérieure - Article R522-1 |language=fr |website=Legifrance |date= |accessdate=2016-03-15}}</ref> They cannot legally wear the dress attributed to the ''police municipale'' (marine blue with a clear blue trimming).

[[File:Grades GC.jpg|thumb|center|400px|Rank insignia from left to right : <br>''Garde Champêtre principal stagiaire<br>Garde Champêtre principal titulaire<br>Garde Champêtre chef<br>Garde Champêtre chef principal'']]
