{{Infobox military installation | name = Kopay Army Base | native_name = | partof = | location = [[Kopay]] | country = [[Sri Lanka]] | image = | caption = | pushpin_map = Sri Lanka Northern Province | pushpin_map_caption = Location within Northern Province | coordinates = {{Coord|09|42|23.30|N|80|02|56.10|E|region:LK_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | type = Military base | site_area = | ownership = [[Ministry of Defence and Urban Development]] | operator = [[Sri Lanka Army]] | controlledby = [[Security Forces Headquarters – Jaffna]] | open_to_public = No | built = | used = | current_commander = | garrison = [[51 Division (Sri Lanka)|51 Division]] | website = }} '''Kopay Army Base''' is a [[military base]] in [[Kopay]], [[Sri Lanka]]. The base was built on a [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] [[war cemetery]].
==History== [[File:Flags Kopai Heroes Graveyard Jaffna 2004.jpg|thumbnail|left|Kopay war cemetery in 2004]] In the early 1990s, when the [[Sri Lankan Tamil militant groups|rebel]] [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (LTTE) controlled the [[Valikamam]] region of [[Jaffna peninsula]], they built a ''thuyilum illam'' (resting place) for their ''maaveerar'' (great heroes) in [[Kopay]]. After the [[Sri Lankan military]] recaptured Valikamam in 1995 they destroyed the LTTE cemetery using tractors.<ref name=TN291106>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka Army bulldozes Heroes' Cemetery in Trincomalee - Elilan|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?artid=20440&catid=13|work=[[TamilNet]]|date=29 November 2006}}</ref><ref name=AT260311>{{cite news|last1=Ramachandran|first1=Sudha|title=Colombo digs grave for Tamil harmony|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/MC26Df02.html|work=[[Asia Times Online]]|date=26 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka builds police station on LTTE cemetery|url=http://tamilguardian.com/article.asp?articleid=1470|work=[[Tamil Guardian]]|date=28 November 2007}}</ref> After the Norwegian mediated peace process began in 2002 the LTTE started rebuilding their war cemeteries including that at Kopay.<ref name=TN291106/><ref name=AT260311/> After the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]] ended in May 2009 with military defeat of the LTTE the Sri Lankan government/military re-commenced destroying LTTE war cemeteries and other memorials for dead LTTE members.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Natarajan|first1=Swaminathan|title=Why Sri Lankan Tamils won't remember war dead this year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11846369|work=[[BBC News]]|date=27 November 2010}}</ref> In July 2010 the Sri Lankan military destroyed Kopay war cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|title=SLA demolishes Koappaay Thamizh Eezham Heroes Cemeteries|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=32116|work=[[TamilNet]]|date=4 July 2010}}</ref> The cemetery had had 2,000 graves.<ref name=BBC070311>{{cite news|last1=Haviland|first1=Charles|title=Sri Lanka builds army HQ on Tamil Tiger cemetery|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-12668613|work=[[BBC News]]|date=7 March 2011}}</ref>
The Sri Lankan military then started building an army base on the site of the cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|last1=DiManno|first1=Rosie|title=Sri Lanka's Tamils face violence, intimidation ahead of provincial vote|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2013/09/21/sri_lankas_tamils_face_violence_intimidation_ahead_of_provincial_vote.html|work=[[Toronto Star]]|date=21 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Amerasinghe|first1=Premini|title=A journey back in time to a place where peace seems surreal|url=http://sundaytimes.lk/111211/Plus/plus_13.html|work=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]]|date=11 December 2011}}</ref> On 4 March 2011 the new headquarters of the [[Sri Lanka Army]]'s [[51 Division (Sri Lanka)|51 Division]] was officially opened by [[Jagath Jayasuriya]], [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Army]].<ref name=BBC070311/><ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lankan state shows ‘reconciliation’ in the country of Eezham Tamils|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=33627|work=[[TamilNet]]|date=5 March 2011}}</ref>
